  • Make a graph object of the tree by two ways; using the edge list and the adjacency matrix.
    • with edge list
    • with adjacency matrix
  • Give positive integer values to the edges and provide the edge weight to the graph object(s).
  • Obtain pairwise distance matrix between all vertex pairs.

Make a graph object of the tree by two ways; using the edge list and the adjacency matrix.

with edge list

edge_list <- c(1,2,1,3,1,4,1,5,1,6,3,7,4,8,4,9,6,10,7,11,7,12,7,13,9,14,9,15,10,16,10,17)
g1 <- graph(edges=edge_list, n=17, directed=F)
plot(g1, main="graph from edges-list")

with adjacency matrix

adj.mat <- matrix(g1[], 17, 17)
g2 <- graph.adjacency(adj.mat, mode='undirected')
plot(g2, layout=layout_as_tree(g2), main="graph from adjacency-matrix")

Give positive integer values to the edges and provide the edge weight to the graph object(s).

g3 <- g1
weight_list <- c(6.5, 5.4, 3.4, 4.2, 7.2, 4.3, 3.0, 2.5, 3.0, 3.5, 2.7, 4.0, 3.0, 3.1, 2.5, 4.8)
E(g3)$label <- c(1:16)
E(g3)$weight <- weight_list
plot(g3, vertex.size=10, edge.label=E(g3)$weight, edge.width=E(g3)$weight, layout=layout_as_tree(g3), main="weighted graph")

Obtain pairwise distance matrix between all vertex pairs.

dis.mat <- matrix(g3[], 17, 17)
